"links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6347"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13728"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34948"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"1440"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11631"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31233"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43915"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49666"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother with a two-week history of rectal bleeding. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. His mother mentions that her brother was diagnosed with colon cancer at a young age. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His abdomen is soft and non-tender. Digital rectal examination reveals no palpable masses. Investigations show a haemoglobin of 110 g/L (130-180) and his faecal occult blood test his positive. Colonoscopy shows numerous (\u0026gt;100) polyps throughout the colon and rectum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Referral to a geneticist for APC mutation testing","Reassurance and discharge","Referral for colectomy","High fibre diet","Repeat colonoscopy in 10 years"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAlmost certainly this is a case of familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP). This condition is the result of a germline mutation in the APC gene, which is inherited in an autosomal dominant fashion. The next step in management should be \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral to a geneticist for APC mutation testing\u003C/strong\u003E. Genetic testing can confirm the diagnosis and then guide screening for at-risk family members.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the patient is currently asymptomatic apart from rectal bleeding, \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance and discharge\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the very high lifetime risk (nearly 100%) of developing colorectal cancer if left untreated. Close surveillance and at some stage prophylactic colectomy are essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for colectomy\u003C/strong\u003E will likely be necessary in the near future to prevent colorectal cancer. However, genetic testing and counseling should occur first to confirm the diagnosis and discuss the implications for the patient and his family.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh fibre diet\u003C/strong\u003E may have some benefit in reducing polyp burden but is not sufficient as a standalone treatment for FAP given the very high polyp burden and cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeating colonoscopy in 10 years\u003C/strong\u003E would be unsafe and inappropriate. Patients with familial adenomatous polyposis require annual colonoscopy surveillance starting from diagnosis until a prophylactic colectomy is performed, usually in late teenage years or early adulthood.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Familial adenomatous polyposis is an inherited condition characterised by the development of numerous polyps in the colon and rectum, often during adolescence.","Familial adenomatous polyposis is caused by a mutation in the APC gene and carries a very high lifetime risk of colorectal cancer if untreated."],"references":["Chung DC, Rodgers LH. Clinical manifestations and diagnosis of familial adenomatous polyposis. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/clinical-manifestations-and-diagnosis-of-familial-adenomatous-polyposis","Kyriakidis F, Kogias D, Venou TM, Karlafti E, Paramythiotis D. Updated Perspectives on the Diagnosis and Management of Familial Adenomatous Polyposis. Appl Clin Genet. 2023 Aug 14;16:139-153. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10439286/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34948"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13728"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34948"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-03T09:06:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-03T09:06:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6347"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49666"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms